answers.body_markdown:
First define your `placeholders` in your `application.properties` file like

    spring.flyway.placeholders.first=FirstValue
    spring.flyway.placeholders.second=SecondValue
    spring.flyway.placeholders.third=ThirdValue

And in your `SQL migration script`, you can use these placeholders as follows:

    INSERT INTO your_table (column_name) VALUES (&#39;${first}&#39;);
    INSERT INTO your_table (column_name) VALUES (&#39;${second}&#39;);
    INSERT INTO your_table (column_name) VALUES (&#39;${third}&#39;);

However, if you want to loop through a `dynamic list` and `insert values` into the database based on that list, it&#39;s generally not possible in a `Flyway migration script` using placeholders, as SQL scripts are typically static. 

Instead, you would typically use a programming language `(like Java or a scripting language)` to loop through the list and execute the necessary SQL statements.

