answers.body_markdown:
This cannot easily be checked with Spring Security as far as I know, and would likely require some (ugly) reflection (which can be seen in [this article](https://www.baeldung.com/spring-deny-access)). 

An alternative is to write a unit test for this with [ArchUnit](https://www.archunit.org/). ArchUnit has a clean(er) API, and has the benefit that you can run this during your test-phase rather than having to run or deploy your application first, and then rely on end users noticing some forbidden error.

Such a test would look something like this:

```java
@Test
void ensureEachControllerHasPreAuthorize() {
    JavaClasses importedClasses = new ClassFileImporter().importPackages(&quot;com.example.demo&quot;);
    ArchRule rule = methods().that()
        .areMetaAnnotatedWith(RequestMapping.class)
        .and().areDeclaredInClassesThat().areMetaAnnotatedWith(Controller.class)
        .should().beAnnotatedWith(PreAuthorize.class)
        .orShould().beDeclaredInClassesThat().areAnnotatedWith(PreAuthorize.class);
    rule.check(importedClasses);
}
```

Some remarks:

* The `areMetaAnnotatedWith(RequestMapping.class)` includes both `@RequestMapping` and variants like `@GetMapping`, `@PostMapping`, ... .
* Same applies to the `areMetaAnnotatedWith(Controller.class)` which includes both `@Controller` and `@RestController`.
* I&#39;m allowing both controller methods and classes to be annotated with `@PreAuthorize`. If you only want to pass the test if `@PreAuthorize` is applied on method-level and not at class-level, then you can remove the line that starts with `orShould()`.
* ArchUnit isn&#39;t included by default in any of the Spring Boot starters. You&#39;ll have to include the dependency by yourself.

